			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&message.id=1936#M1936">59</a> of 113
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 473 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<DIV>I think the point is that we are one of, if not the only, class that is required to pay such a constant and annoying cost for our buffs. The content is now geared to pretty much require a symbol on content. You are lucky if you can cast an HoV and have it last for the full 4 hours extended. With deaths, and new people coming and going I usually go through anywhere from 3-8 peridots in an experience group. thats 30-80 platinum. I'm 65, and have mostly no drop gear, and all my spells, so the only thing I have to spend plat on is tradeskills. But it is still annoying. HoV is all our best buffs rolled into one, and it costs 2500 mana to cast along with 2 peridots. Druid's "best" spell, arguably, is Po9. I don't know how much it costs to cast, I don't know whether or not it is a group of all their best buffs rolled into one. I do know that it doesn't stack with HoV though. Instead, to get the best effect I have to combine 9, with Kazad and WoG. Guess what, it still ends up costing me 2 peridots. Shaman's "best" spell that is used as a HP buff is Focus, again, no peridot cost. The best analogous spell though is the enchanter KEI line. These spells are all combos of their best buffs, essentially they are a clarity/int/wis/mana pool buff, that is then extended to last for like 2 hours longer then any of the individual spells last on their own. Unlike Clerics though, their "best" buff doesn't cost them one red cent. Furthermore, and I find this particularly irritating, they get several items that allow them to cast their best buff mana free via right clickies. There is the KEI rod from VT that is basically a money rod. Then they get clicky Tranquility on their Ornate pants. Where is my Virtue rod, or my right click Virtue pants? These aren't buffs that are nice to have, they are pretty much a requirement in most groups to maximize the experience, yet our class is the only one that is required to pay through the nose for 30 levels. Oh, and one more ridiculous slap in the face. Avatar. Now, I sincerely feel for the shaman who are expected to cast this spell. Its what, 6 minute duration unextended, and costs an emerald? Now, that sucks. But, lo and behold, (i) tons of folks can get this spell as a proc on their ST weapons, thus making it not such a burden, (ii) they aren't expected to cast it on everyone in the group, nor could they keep it going all the time due to its duration even if they wanted to, and (iii) the worst slap in the face of all, at 65 they get Ferine Avatar which is, you guessed it, a componentless version of this spell. You can sit there and say that cleric buffs "should" cost a component because they are so good. Well, in that case then Focus and 9 should require a component to by that reasoning because they are so good too, and maybe Ferine Avatar should require two emeralds because it is sooo good? Oh, and remember, Divine Intervention costs, not one peridot, not two peridots, not one emerald, but in fact TWO emeralds every time you cast it, and Blessing of Aegolism costs FOUR peridots per cast. Other classes certainly have costs involved, necro pets for example cost a peridot at high levels, and situationally, a Wizard can blow through a ton of peridots casting Spell Shield over and over again. But no one is required to keep SS up on a group all the time. The time for the oppression of clerics due to component costs is over. I say in the next expansion they require all the other classes best spells to require double mana and double peridots and see what kind of outcry is raised. The game wouldn't go two weeks without the components being removed for the other classes. We are going on 5 years for clerics, and its looking like they intend us to bear the burden in OOW as well.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Vykadin</DIV>	
		</td></tr>
